For a periodically driven Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}(t)$
\end_inset

 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, Floquet operator is defined as,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{F}=\hat{\mathcal{T}}\exp\{-i\int_{T_{i}}^{T_{i}+T}dt\hat{H}(t)\}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 denotes time-order, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the initial time.
 The eigenvalue and eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{F}|\varphi_{n}\rangle=e^{-i\varepsilon_{n}T}|\varphi_{n}\rangle,\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi/T<\varepsilon_{n}<\pi/T$
\end_inset

 is the quasi-energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time-ordering operator can be written in terms of ordered product of
 exponentials in the infinite limit of number of terms 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\hat{F} & = & \hat{\mathcal{T}}\exp\{-i\left(\int_{T_{i}}^{T_{i}+\Delta T}dt\hat{H}(T_{i})+\int_{T_{i}+\Delta T}^{T_{i}+2\Delta T}dt\hat{H}(T_{i}+\Delta T)+...+\int_{T_{i}+T-\Delta T}^{T_{i}+T}dt\hat{H}(T_{i}+T-\Delta T)\right)\}\\
 & = & \hat{\mathcal{T}}\exp\{-i\Delta T\left(\hat{H}(T_{i})+\hat{H}(T_{i}+\Delta T)+...+\hat{H}(T_{i}+T-\Delta T)\right)\}\\
 & = & \lim_{M\rightarrow\infty}\left(e^{-i\hat{H}(t_{M-1})\Delta T}e^{-i\hat{H}(t_{M-2})\Delta T}\dots e^{-i\hat{H}(t_{0})\Delta T}\right)\\
 & \approx & \exp\{-i\hat{H}(T_{i}+T-\Delta T)\Delta T\}\exp\{-i\hat{H}(T_{i}+T-2\Delta T)\Delta T\}...\exp\{-i\hat{H}(T_{i})\Delta T\}\\
 & \equiv & \exp\{-i\hat{H}(t_{M-1})\Delta T\}\exp\{-i\hat{H}(t_{M-2})\Delta T\}...\exp\{-i\hat{H}(t_{0})\Delta T\}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we have devided the time interval from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}+T$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=T/M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}=T_{i}+jT/M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,...M-1$
\end_inset

.
 Numerically, we will introduce a cutoff 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{max}}$
\end_inset

 for finite terms.
 We can make use of eigenvalue decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
H(t) & = & V(t)D(t)V(t)^{\dagger}\\
e^{-iH(t)\Delta t} & = & V(t)e^{-iD(t)\Delta t}V(t)^{\dagger}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

(it is worth to note that this method is more stable than Taylor expansion
 to 2nd, 4th(RK) order, similiar to algorithm used in MATLAB function of
 expm or 
\begin_inset Formula $exp$
\end_inset

 subroutine in 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "unsupported module of Eigen C++ library"
target "http://eigen.tuxfamily.org/dox/unsupported/group__MatrixFunctions__Module.html"

\end_inset

) then we have ,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F=\lim_{M\rightarrow\infty}\left(V(t_{M-1})e^{-iD(t_{M-1})\Delta t}V(t_{M-1})^{\dagger}V(t_{M-2})e^{-iD(t_{M-2})\Delta t}V(t_{M-2})^{\dagger}\dots V(t_{0})e^{-iD(t_{0})\Delta t}V(t_{0})^{\dagger}\right)\end{equation}

\end_inset

where exponential of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is evaluated only for the diagonal terms, which are the eigenvalue terms.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Each exponential matrix is further approximated by Taylor expansion up to
 second order
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
e^{-iH(t_{j})\Delta t}\approx I-iH(t_{j})\Delta t-\frac{1}{2}H(t_{j})H(t_{j})(\Delta t)^{2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which turns out to be difficult to treat exactly because at different time
 the Hamiltonian matrix does not commute.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To make some progress, we treat operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 as a function of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the end result of one period expression is equivalent to integrate
 the differential equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\hat{F}(T_{i}+t,T_{i})=-i\hat{H}(t)\hat{F}(T_{i}+t,T_{i})\label{eq:diffFloquet}\end{equation}

\end_inset

up to 
\begin_inset Formula $t=T$
\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}(T_{i},T_{i})=I_{4N_{max}\times4N_{max}}$
\end_inset

.
 We adopt the Runge-Kutta method to integrate the Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffFloquet"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F(T_{i}+t_{j+1},T_{i})=F(T_{i}+t_{j},T_{i})-\frac{i\delta t}{6}(k_{1}+2k_{2}+2k_{3}+k_{4})\label{eq:RKFloquet}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=T/M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
k_{1} & = & H(t_{j})F(t_{j})\\
k_{2} & = & H(t_{j})(F(t_{j})+\frac{\delta t}{2}k_{1})=(1+\frac{\delta t}{2}H(t_{j}))\cdot k_{1}\\
k_{3} & = & H(t_{j})(F(t_{j})+\frac{\delta t}{2}k_{2})=k_{1}+\frac{\delta t}{2}H(t_{j})\cdot k_{2}\\
k_{4} & = & H(t_{j})(F(t_{j})+\delta tk_{3})=k_{1}+\frac{\delta t}{2}H(t_{j})\cdot k_{3}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

In order to get rid of matrix storage for 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{4}$
\end_inset

, we write Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RKFloquet"

\end_inset

 explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F'=\left[I-i\delta t\left(H+\frac{\delta t}{2}H^{2}+\frac{(\delta t)^{2}}{6}H^{3}+\frac{(\delta t)^{3}}{24}H^{4}\right)\right]F\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we only need to have storage of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
